    {"doc_id": "ai_006", "title": "Embedding models and semantic similarity",
     "body": "Sentence embedding models like all-MiniLM-L6-v2 and text-embedding-3-large map text to fixed-dimensional vectors where cosine similarity reflects semantic similarity. These models are trained with contrastive learning on sentence pairs. Larger models (1536-dim OpenAI embeddings) outperform smaller ones on MTEB benchmarks but cost more to run.",
     "domain": "ai", "source": "nlp"},
    {"doc_id": "ai_007", "title": "Model Context Protocol for AI agents",
     "body": "MCP is an open standard for connecting AI assistants to external data sources and tools. It uses JSON-RPC 2.0 over stdio or SSE transport. MCP servers expose tools, resources, and prompts; clients (like Claude Desktop) discover and invoke them. The protocol standardises tool discovery, replacing ad-hoc function-calling integrations.",
     "domain": "ai", "source": "agents"},
    {"doc_id": "ai_008", "title": "LangGraph multi-agent orchestration",
     "body": "LangGraph models agent workflows as directed graphs where nodes are LLM calls or tool invocations and edges are transitions. Conditional edges enable branching on model output. It supports cycles (reflection loops), parallel branches, and stateful conversation management. StateGraph and MessageGraph are the two main graph types.",
     "domain": "ai", "source": "agents"},
    {"doc_id": "ai_009", "title": "Mixture of experts architecture",
     "body": "MoE models route each input token to a subset of expert FFN layers rather than all parameters simultaneously. A learned router selects top-K experts per token (typically 2 out of 8 or 64). This enables very large parameter counts while keeping per-token compute constant. Mistral and Mixtral use MoE; GPT-4 is rumoured to.",
     "domain": "ai", "source": "deep_learning"},
    {"doc_id": "ai_010", "title": "Speculative decoding for LLM inference",
     "body": "Speculative decoding uses a small draft model to propose multiple tokens at once, which a larger target model then accepts or rejects in parallel. Accepted tokens produce a speedup because the target model evaluates a batch rather than single tokens. Speedups of 2-3x are achievable without quality loss.",
     "domain": "ai", "source": "inference"},
    {"doc_id": "ai_011", "title": "Flash attention and memory efficiency",
     "body": "FlashAttention computes exact attention without materialising the full N×N attention matrix in HBM (GPU high-bandwidth memory). It tiles the computation into SRAM-sized blocks, reducing memory bandwidth from O(N²) to O(N). FlashAttention-2 and -3 further improve by reducing non-matmul FLOPs and exploiting tensor core layouts.",
     "domain": "ai", "source": "inference"},
    {"doc_id": "ai_012", "title": "Quantisation for LLM deployment",
     "body": "Quantisation reduces model weight precision from float32 (4 bytes) or bfloat16 (2 bytes) to int8 (1 byte) or int4 (0.5 bytes). GPTQ and AWQ are popular post-training quantisation methods for LLMs. 4-bit quantisation reduces memory by 8x with minimal quality loss on most benchmarks.",
     "domain": "ai", "source": "inference"},
    {"doc_id": "ai_013", "title": "CHORUS Fabric tensor communication protocol",
     "body": "CHORUS Fabric is a patent-pending tensor-native communication protocol for AI agents. Instead of serialising float32 embeddings to JSON text, CHORUS streams vectors directly with a matrix-multiply cipher (V_enc = V_raw @ K using QR-decomposed orthogonal keys). Live transatlantic benchmarks show 4.45x less bandwidth than HTTP/REST and 0ms cipher overhead.",
     "domain": "ai", "source": "agents"},
    {"doc_id": "ai_014", "title": "AI agent memory and context management",
     "body": "Long-horizon agents need persistent memory across interactions. Approaches include in-context storage (limited by context window), vector memory (embed and retrieve past interactions), and external databases. Episodic memory stores specific past events; semantic memory stores distilled facts; procedural memory stores learned skills.",
     "domain": "ai", "source": "agents"},
    {"doc_id": "ai_015", "title": "Hallucination detection and grounding",
     "body": "LLMs hallucinate plausible-sounding but false statements. Detection methods include consistency checking (ask the same question multiple ways), citation verification (check claims against retrieved sources), and specialised classifiers trained on hallucination datasets. RAG reduces hallucination on knowledge-intensive tasks by providing grounding evidence.",
     "domain": "ai", "source": "alignment"},
    {"doc_id": "ai_016", "title": "RLHF alternatives: DPO and GRPO",
     "body": "Direct Preference Optimisation eliminates the separate reward model by deriving training signal directly from preference pairs. GRPO (Group Relative Policy Optimisation) computes rewards relative to a group of completions rather than a reference model baseline. Both are simpler than PPO-based RLHF and have shown competitive results.",
     "domain": "ai", "source": "alignment"},
    {"doc_id": "ai_017", "title": "Multimodal models and vision-language",
     "body": "Vision-language models like GPT-4V, Gemini Ultra, and Claude 3 Opus process both images and text. Vision encoders (ViT or convolutional) extract visual features that are projected into the language model's embedding space. Capabilities include chart understanding, OCR, image description, and visual question answering.",
     "domain": "ai", "source": "multimodal"},
    {"doc_id": "ai_018", "title": "Prompt engineering techniques",
     "body": "Chain-of-thought prompting asks models to reason step-by-step before giving an answer, improving performance on multi-step problems. Few-shot prompting provides examples to guide output format. Tree-of-thought explores multiple reasoning branches. ReAct interleaves reasoning and tool actions. Structured output constrains generation to JSON schemas.",
     "domain": "ai", "source": "llm"},
    {"doc_id": "ai_019", "title": "AI safety and alignment research",
     "body": "Alignment research aims to ensure AI systems behave in accordance with human values and intentions. Key problems include reward hacking (achieving high reward through unintended means), specification gaming, and inner alignment (trained model's goals differing from training objective). Interpretability research attempts to understand model internals.",
     "domain": "ai", "source": "alignment"},
    {"doc_id": "ai_020", "title": "Federated learning and privacy preservation",
     "body": "Federated learning trains models across distributed data sources without centralising raw data. Clients train locally and share only model updates (gradients) with a central server. Differential privacy adds calibrated noise to gradients to prevent reconstruction of training data. Applications include medical AI and mobile keyboard prediction.",
     "domain": "ai", "source": "privacy"},

